  "ancestors": [
    {
      "code": "ofs",
      "role": "parent",
      "weight": 0.8,
      "notes": "Descent from Old Frisian (East Frisian branch). Saterland Frisian is the last surviving dialect of East Frisian, spoken in the Saterland (Seelterland) municipalities since medieval Frisian colonisation of the bogs."
    },
    {
      "code": "nds",
      "role": "adstrate",
      "weight": 0.1,
      "notes": "Low German adstrate: Saterland is surrounded by Low German speakers. Heavy Low German influence on lexicon and some phonological convergence, especially in younger speakers."
    },
    {
      "code": "de-DE",
      "role": "adstrate",
      "weight": 0.07,
      "notes": "Standard German adstrate: dominant language of education and administration. All Saterland Frisians are trilingual (Saterland Frisian, Low German, Standard German)."
    },
    {
      "code": "nl",
      "role": "adstrate",
      "weight": 0.03,
      "notes": "Dutch adstrate: historical trade contacts with the Netherlands; some Dutch-influenced lexical items, particularly in older vocabulary."
    }
  ],
  "notes": "Saterland Frisian (Seeltersk) — the last surviving variety of East Frisian, spoken by ~1,000–2,500 people in the four Saterland municipalities (Ramsloh, Strücklingen, Scharrel, Sedelsberg) in the Cloppenburg district of Lower Saxony, Germany. Severely endangered; recognised as a minority language under the European Charter. KEY FEATURES: (1) MOST CONSERVATIVE FRISIAN: preserves features lost in West and North Frisian, including some Old Frisian vowel distinctions and diphthong patterns. (2) CENTRING DIPHTHONGS /iə, oə, uə/ — shared Frisian heritage. (3) FINAL DEVOICING as in all Frisian and continental West Germanic. (4) VOICED STOP /ɡ/ — retained from Old Frisian. (5) /sp, st/ → [ʃp, ʃt] word-initially (shared with Low German). (6) /s/ → [z] intervocalically and word-initially before vowels. (7) RICH FRONT ROUNDED VOWELS: ö/öö, ü/üü from i-umlaut. (8) Long ää /ɛː/ preserved as distinct from ee /eː/. (9) THREE-LANGUAGE ecology: all speakers also speak Low German and Standard German. Sources: Fort (1980), Markey (1981), Kramer (1982).",
